%% AutomationOS Interrupt Handling Sequence
%% Mermaid Sequence Diagram

sequenceDiagram
    participant Dev as Device<br/>(e.g., Keyboard)
    participant PIC as PIC<br/>(8259A)
    participant CPU as CPU
    participant IDT as IDT<br/>(Interrupt Descriptor Table)
    participant ISR as ISR Handler<br/>(interrupt.asm)
    participant Driver as Device Driver<br/>(ps2.c)
    participant Kernel as Kernel<br/>(Process/Buffer)

    Note over Dev,Kernel: Example: Keyboard key press

    Dev->>PIC: Assert IRQ 1 signal
    activate PIC
    Note over PIC: Keyboard controller<br/>raises hardware interrupt

    PIC->>PIC: Check IRQ mask<br/>(IMR - Interrupt Mask Register)

    alt IRQ masked
        Note over PIC: Interrupt ignored<br/>(IRQ bit set in IMR)
        PIC-->>Dev: No interrupt delivered
    else IRQ enabled
        PIC->>CPU: INTR signal raised
        activate CPU

        CPU->>CPU: Check RFLAGS.IF<br/>(Interrupt Enable Flag)

        alt Interrupts disabled
            Note over CPU: IF=0<br/>Interrupt deferred
        else Interrupts enabled
            CPU->>CPU: Finish current instruction<br/>(instruction boundary)

            Note over CPU: Hardware interrupt sequence:<br/>1. Push SS, RSP (if privilege change)<br/>2. Push RFLAGS<br/>3. Clear IF (disable interrupts)<br/>4. Push CS, RIP<br/>5. Read interrupt vector from PIC

            PIC-->>CPU: IRQ 1 → Vector 33<br/>(IRQ 0-15 mapped to 32-47)
            deactivate PIC

            CPU->>IDT: Lookup IDT[33]
            activate IDT
            Note over IDT: IDT entry:<br/>• Offset: ISR address<br/>• Segment: kernel CS<br/>• DPL: 0 (kernel only)<br/>• Type: Interrupt Gate

            IDT-->>CPU: ISR address
            deactivate IDT

            CPU->>ISR: Jump to ISR
            deactivate CPU
            activate ISR

            Note over ISR: Common ISR stub:<br/>• Push error code (0)<br/>• Push interrupt number (33)<br/>• Save all GPRs

            ISR->>Driver: Call device handler:<br/>keyboard_handler()
            activate Driver

            Driver->>Dev: Read scancode from keyboard<br/>inb(0x60)
            activate Dev
            Dev-->>Driver: Scancode (e.g., 0x1E = 'a')
            deactivate Dev

            Driver->>Driver: Translate scancode<br/>to ASCII character

            Driver->>Kernel: Add to input buffer<br/>or send to process
            activate Kernel
            Note over Kernel: Store in TTY buffer<br/>or wake waiting process
            Kernel-->>Driver: Buffer updated
            deactivate Kernel

            Driver-->>ISR: Handler complete
            deactivate Driver

            ISR->>PIC: Send EOI<br/>(End of Interrupt)<br/>outb(0x20, 0x20)
            activate PIC
            Note over PIC: Clear IRQ in service bit<br/>Allow new interrupts
            PIC-->>ISR: EOI acknowledged
            deactivate PIC

            ISR->>ISR: Restore all GPRs<br/>Pop error code and vector

            ISR->>CPU: iretq instruction
            deactivate ISR
            activate CPU

            Note over CPU: Hardware return:<br/>1. Pop CS, RIP<br/>2. Pop RFLAGS (restore IF)<br/>3. Pop SS, RSP (if privilege change)

            CPU-->>Kernel: Resume interrupted code
            deactivate CPU
        end
    end

    Note over Dev,Kernel: Interrupt latency breakdown:<br/>• PIC to CPU: ~0.1 μs<br/>• CPU state save: ~0.2 μs<br/>• ISR handler: ~1-5 μs<br/>• State restore: ~0.2 μs<br/>Total: ~1.5-5.5 μs

    Note over Dev,Kernel: Nested Interrupts:<br/>• IF cleared on entry (no nesting by default)<br/>• Can be enabled explicitly for high-priority IRQs<br/>• Requires separate interrupt stacks (IST)
